Think of Docker as managing images (blueprints) and containers (running instances).

Step 1: Search for an image

You want to run Nginx but don't know the exact image name.

docker search nginx

Story: "Is there an Nginx image available on Docker Hub?"

Step 2: Download the image
docker pull nginx

Story: "Download the Nginx blueprint (image) to my computer."

Step 3: Check downloaded images
docker images

Story: "Show me all the blueprints I have."

Output might show:

REPOSITORY   TAG     IMAGE ID
nginx        latest  abc123
ubuntu       latest  xyz456
Step 4: Create and start a container

Most people use:

docker run nginx

Story: "Take the Nginx blueprint, create a container from it, and start it."

Docker internally does something like:

Image
   ↓
Create Container
   ↓
Start Container
Step 5: See running containers
docker ps

Story: "Which containers are currently running?"

Step 6: See all containers
docker ps -a

Story: "Show both running and stopped containers."

Example:

nginx1   Running
ubuntu1  Exited
Step 7: Stop a container
docker stop nginx1

Story: "Stop the Nginx container."

The container still exists—it just isn't running.

Step 8: Start it again
docker start nginx1

Story: "Start the same container again."

Step 9 (Optional): Create without starting

Instead of docker run, suppose you only want to prepare the container.

docker create nginx

Story: "Create the container, but don't start it yet."

Later:

docker start <container_id>

This is equivalent to:

docker create nginx
docker start <container_id>

whereas

docker run nginx

does both steps automatically.

Step 10: Remove the container

First stop it:

docker stop nginx1

Then remove it:

docker rm nginx1

Story: "I'm done with this container. Delete it."

Step 11: Remove the image

Once no containers are using the image:

docker rmi nginx

Story: "Delete the blueprint too."

If any container (running or stopped) still uses the image, Docker will refuse to remove it.

Complete story
docker search nginx
        ↓
docker pull nginx
        ↓
docker images
        ↓
docker run nginx
        ↓
docker ps
        ↓
docker stop <container>
        ↓
docker start <container>
        ↓
docker stop <container>
        ↓
docker rm <container>
        ↓
docker rmi nginx
Remember the difference
docker pull → Download an image.
docker create → Create a container but don't start it.
docker run → Create and start a container (and pull the image first if it's not already available locally).



                                           This is one of the most confusing parts of Docker at first. The key is understanding what each one contains.

Let's use a school project analogy.

Suppose you've written a Java application.

1. Sharing only your code 📄

You zip your project and send it to your friend.

BankApp/
    src/
    pom.xml

Your friend now has your code.

But they still need to figure out:

Which operating system?
Which JDK version?
Maven or Gradle?
Environment variables?
Database?
Any other software?

So they ask:

"How do I run this?"

You reply with instructions.

2. Dockerfile 📝

A Dockerfile is NOT the application.

It is NOT the image.

It is simply a recipe for building an image.

Example:

FROM ubuntu

RUN apt install openjdk-21

COPY . /app

WORKDIR /app

RUN mvn package

CMD ["java","-jar","bank.jar"]

Read it like this:

Start with Ubuntu.

Install Java.

Copy my code.

Compile it.

When someone starts this image, run my application.

Notice something?

The Dockerfile does not contain Java.

It doesn't contain Ubuntu.

It doesn't contain your dependencies.

It just says how to get them.

Think of it as a cooking recipe.

Recipe:

Take flour.
Add eggs.
Bake for 30 minutes.

The recipe doesn't contain flour or eggs.

3. Docker Image 📦

Now Docker reads the Dockerfile and performs every step.

FROM ubuntu
↓
Download Ubuntu

Install Java
↓
Java installed

Copy code
↓
Code copied

Build project
↓
JAR created

After everything finishes...

Docker creates an image.

This image actually contains:

Ubuntu
Java
Libraries
Your JAR
Configuration
Everything needed

Think of it as a sealed lunch box.

Everything is already inside.

No cooking required anymore.

4. Container 🚀

Now you say

docker run bank-image

Docker opens the lunch box.

Your application starts running.

That running application is the container.

Think of it like this:

Image
     ↓
Run
     ↓
Container
Real-life analogy

Imagine you're making instant noodles.

Code
Ingredients list

Not enough to make noodles.

Dockerfile
Boil water.

Add noodles.

Cook for 2 minutes.

Recipe only.

Image
Ready-to-cook noodle kit.

Contains:
✔ noodles
✔ seasoning
✔ bowl

Everything packed.

Container

You pour hot water.

Now you're actually eating the noodles.

The container is the meal you're eating.

Why not just share the Dockerfile?

Excellent question.

Suppose your Dockerfile says

FROM ubuntu

Your friend builds it tomorrow.

Ubuntu may have changed.

Maybe Java version changed.

Maybe Maven downloads a newer dependency.

So the resulting image might not be exactly the same.

An image avoids that uncertainty because it's already been built.

Then why share Dockerfiles at all?

Because developers usually share both:

Project
│
├── source code
├── Dockerfile
└── README

The Dockerfile lets anyone rebuild the image if needed.

But when deploying to production, teams often share the image, because it has already been built and tested.

The complete picture
Your Java code
        │
        ▼
Dockerfile
(Instructions to build)
        │
        ▼
docker build
        │
        ▼
Docker Image
(Packaged application + OS + Java + dependencies)
        │
        ▼
docker run
        │
        ▼
Docker Container
(Running application)
The one sentence that usually makes it click
Code = "Here's my project."
Dockerfile = "Here's how to package and run my project."
Docker Image = "Here's the packaged project, ready to use."
Docker Container = "Here's the packaged project currently running."

The Dockerfile is similar to sharing code plus instructions, but it's more powerful because it's machine-readable. Instead of a human following a README ("Install Java 21, then Maven, then..."), Docker itself executes the instructions and produces the same packaged image every time.
